 "explanation": {
 "raw_text": "Summary: The analysis of the withdrawal signal trend indicates a declining engagement among students who eventually withdrew, particularly evident in the sharp drop in average clicks during specific weeks. This trend suggests that early detection of potential dropouts can be achieved by monitoring engagement metrics closely.\n\nInsights: Sharp Drop in Engagement: There was a significant decline in avg_clicks from week 11 to week 12, where avg_clicks fell from 41.17 to 38.45, indicating a potential early warning signal for students at risk of withdrawal. | Engagement Peak and Trough: The highest engagement was recorded in week 1 with avg_clicks at 138.61, while the lowest was in week 12 at 38.45. This suggests that students who withdrew exhibited a drastic decline in engagement over time.\n\nEducational implications: Monitoring engagement metrics, particularly avg_clicks, can serve as an early warning system for identifying students at risk of withdrawal.\n\nRecommendations: high - Implement regular monitoring of engagement metrics starting from week 1. - This will allow educators to identify students showing signs of disengagement early and intervene appropriately.\n\nWarnings: 3 Withdrawn points have student_count below 10; avoid over-weighting these weeks.",
